      "the required inequality.\n\n### Step 7: Formal Proof\n\nNow we can fill in the `sorry`. \n\nFirst, get Lemma 1:\n  `ν(G) ≤ ν(G - Y) + Y_encard`.\n\nThen Lemma 2:\n  `2 * ν(G - Y) ≤ (G - Y).vertexSet.encard - (G - Y).oddComponents.encard`.\n\nThen combine them:\n  `2 * ν(G) ≤ 2 * ν(G - Y) + 2 * Y_encard ≤ ...`\n\nBut Lean's `G - Y` is `G.erase Y`, and `(G.erase Y).vertexSet.encard = G.vertexSet.encard - Y_encard` if `Y ⊆ G.vertexSet`.\n\nBut in Lean, `Y : Set α` and there is no assumption that `Y ⊆ G.vertexSet`, so if `Y` has elements not in `G.vertexSet`, then `G.erase Y` is the same as `G`, and `(G.erase Y).vertexSet.encard = G.vertexSet.encard`.\n\nBut the theorem statement is fine because:\n  - If `Y` has elements not in `G`, `Y.encard` increases, but `(G - Y).oddComponents.encard` doesn't change, so the RHS increases.\n  - The LHS doesn't depend on `Y`.\n\nSo we don't actually need to worry about the case `Y ⊈ G.vertexSet`, because the inequality becomes even easier to prove (as the RHS becomes larger). \n\nHowever, in Lean, to avoid problems, we can split into two cases:\n1. If `Y ⊆ G.vertexSet`, then `(G.erase Y).vertexSet.encard = G.vertexSet.encard - Y.encard`.\n2. Otherwise, `(G.erase Y).vertexSet = G.vertexSet`.\n\nBut in the general case, we don't need to know the relation between `(G.erase Y).vertexSet.encard` and `G.vertexSet.encard - Y.encard`, because we can instead use that:\n\n`(G.erase Y).vertexSet.encard + Y.encard ≥ G.vertexSet.encard`.\n\nBut we need to be careful to ensure that all operations are well-defined. \n\nAlternatively, if we have the lemma `2 * ν(H) ≤ H.vertexSet.encard - H.oddComponents.encard`, then for `H = G.erase Y`, we have:\n\n`2 * ν(G.erase Y) ≤ (G.erase Y).vertexSet.encard - (G.erase Y).oddComponents.encard`.\n\nAnd then we need to get `ν(G) ≤ ν(G.erase Y) + Y.encard`.\n\nIn Lean, `Y.encard` is natural number, so if we have `Y ⊆ G.vertexSet`, then `G.erase Y` works well.\n\nAlternatively, since `Y : Set α`, we can do `